{"schema": {"fields":[{"type":"integer","name":"index"},{"type":"string","name":"author_association"},{"type":"string","name":"body"},{"type":"datetime","name":"created_at"},{"type":"string","name":"html_url"},{"type":"integer","name":"id"},{"type":"string","name":"issue_url"},{"type":"string","name":"node_id"},{"type":"datetime","name":"updated_at"},{"type":"string","name":"url"},{"type":"string","name":"user"}],"pandas_version":"0.20.0","primaryKey":["index"]}, "data": [{"index":0,"author_association":"COLLABORATOR","body":"> Ray-casting should ignore the bounding sphere if the caster already starts inside the bounding volume.\r\n\r\nFrom my point of view, this statement is incorrect. _3D Math Primer for Graphics and Game Development_ says in its ray\/sphere intersection test chapter the following:\r\n\r\n_The origin of the ray could be inside the sphere. Appropriate behavior in this case would vary, depending on the purpose of the test._\r\n\r\nAgainst this backdrop, I vote to close the PR since the current implementation is absolutely valid. There is also no breakage because of this change.","created_at":"2018-08-23T14:13:24.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/pull\/10013#issuecomment-415428786","id":415428786,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10013","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQxNTQyODc4Ng==","updated_at":"2018-08-23T14:13:36.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/415428786","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars2.githubusercontent.com\/u\/12612165?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/Mugen87","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEyNjEyMTY1","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"Mugen87","type":"User","id":12612165,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/orgs"}},{"index":1,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"@Mugen87 I'm not sure I agree. While the current implementation might be valid relative to the quoted text, it's pretty confusing that a ray would miss a set of triangles because the ray is starting inside of the bounding volume. From my perspective the point of a raycast here is to check if the ray intersects any triangles in its path and in that respect it would seem that the current approach could miss triangles that you would expect it to hit. Is there a case where the current behavior is preferred to the proposed behavior?\r\n\r\nAt the very least this discrepancy should be very clearly documented. I actually didn't know this was the behavior until I saw this post and it has probably been the source of a few raycasting headaches I've had in the past.","created_at":"2018-08-24T22:24:13.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/pull\/10013#issuecomment-415897944","id":415897944,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10013","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQxNTg5Nzk0NA==","updated_at":"2018-08-24T22:24:13.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/415897944","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars0.githubusercontent.com\/u\/734200?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/gkjohnson","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjczNDIwMA==","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"gkjohnson","type":"User","id":734200,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/orgs"}},{"index":2,"author_association":"OWNER","body":"I just tried creating a long cube in https:\/\/threejs.org\/editor\/ and zooming in very close to it and I'm still able to select it... \ud83e\udd14","created_at":"2018-08-24T23:22:44.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/pull\/10013#issuecomment-415906906","id":415906906,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10013","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQxNTkwNjkwNg==","updated_at":"2018-08-24T23:22:44.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/415906906","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars0.githubusercontent.com\/u\/97088?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjk3MDg4","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"mrdoob","type":"User","id":97088,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/mrdoob\/orgs"}},{"index":3,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"I just tested it a bit, too, and it seems to be a non issue -- looks like my headaches were coming from somewhere else! Here's a jsfiddle showing that raycasting works from inside the bounding volumes:\r\n\r\nhttp:\/\/jsfiddle.net\/5x8wb3cg\/\r\n\r\nThe problem would be present if `Ray.intersectsSphere` or `Ray.intersectsBox` returned false if the ray started inside of the volume, but that doesn't seem to be the case:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nvar ray = new THREE.Ray(new THREE.Vector3(0,0,0), new THREE.Vector3(1,0,0));\r\nvar sphere = new THREE.Sphere(new THREE.Vector3(0, 0, 0), 100);\r\nvar box = new THREE.Box3(new THREE.Vector3(-20, -20, -20), new THREE.Vector3(20, 20, 20));  \r\n\r\nvar sphereIntersect = ray.intersectsSphere(sphere);\r\nvar boxIntersect = ray.intersectsBox(box);\r\nconsole.log(sphereIntersect, boxIntersect); \/\/ true, true\r\n```\r\n","created_at":"2018-08-25T01:26:45.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/pull\/10013#issuecomment-415920426","id":415920426,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10013","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQxNTkyMDQyNg==","updated_at":"2018-08-25T01:26:45.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/415920426","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars0.githubusercontent.com\/u\/734200?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/gkjohnson","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjczNDIwMA==","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"gkjohnson","type":"User","id":734200,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/gkjohnson\/orgs"}},{"index":4,"author_association":"COLLABORATOR","body":"> From my perspective the point of a raycast here is to check if the ray intersects any triangles in its path and in that respect it would seem that the current approach could miss triangles that you would expect it to hit. \r\n\r\nJust to be clear the current implementation does not miss triangles. The OP wanted that there is not intersection detected when the ray starts inside the bounding sphere. I have posted the section from the literature in order to highlight that there is no correct\/wrong approach in this context. Because of this and to maintain backwards compatibility, I vote to keep the current implementation and close the PR.\r\n\r\nBTW: From my personal point of view, the current implementation is better than not detecting intersections when the ray starts inside a bounding volume. A ray starts from a specific point and extends infinitely along a specific direction. It's natural to assume that there is an intersection if the ray starts inside a bounding volume.","created_at":"2018-08-25T09:49:50.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/pull\/10013#issuecomment-415957468","id":415957468,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/10013","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQxNTk1NzQ2OA==","updated_at":"2018-08-25T22:26:58.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/415957468","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.